  <article class="post-content">
    <p>Five launches are scheduled for Q2 2026 that I think genuinely deserve a showflat visit. Here's the shortlist — and why each one matters.</p>

    <h2>The shortlist</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>An RCR launch in the Alexandra precinct</strong> — strong transport, but watch the PSF anchor relative to nearby resale.</li>
      <li><strong>A boutique freehold in District 10</strong> — limited stack count means pricing power, but exit liquidity is the real question.</li>
      <li><strong>A sizeable OCR project near a new MRT extension</strong> — the MRT premium is real, but already partly priced in.</li>
      <li><strong>A redevelopment in District 15</strong> — the East Coast story keeps working; this one's about which stack you pick.</li>
      <li><strong>A mass-market launch in the North</strong> — the value play if PSF lands where I expect.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>What I'll be watching at preview</h2>
    <p>For each project, three questions:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Is the launch PSF defensible against 5-year resale comps within 800 m?</strong></li>
      <li><strong>What's the unit mix?</strong> Heavy 1-bedder skew = investor product, heavier 3-4 bedder skew = owner-occupier product. Resale liquidity diverges sharply between these two.</li>
      <li><strong>Are the stacks priced to move?</strong> If the developer is leaving money on premium stacks, the project will struggle in months 3–6.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The takeaway</h2>
    <p>Don't be the buyer who walks into a showflat without a thesis. Decide what you'd pay before the marketing kicks in — then test it against the price book.</p>
